parliament
and as Iran's president in the
1980s.

17:58.511 --> 18:03.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was also a mentor of their
current president,
Hassan Rouhani, who will be up
for reelection

18:03.983 --> 18:05.618 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
this May.

18:05.651 --> 18:11.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Joining me now to discuss
Rafsanjani, his
influence and Iran going forward
is Karim

18:11.123 --> 18:12.558 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Sadjadpour.

18:12.591 --> 18:15.928 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's a senior fellow at the
Carnegie Endowment
for International Peace.

18:15.962 --> 18:17.463 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Karim, thank you for being back
with us.

18:17.496 --> 18:18.397 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KARIM SADJADPOUR, Carnegie
Endowment For International
Peace: Thank you.

18:18.431 --> 18:19.865 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Thank you, Judy.

18:19.899 --> 18:22.234 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What made
Rafsanjani the influential
figure that he was?

18:22.268 --> 18:26.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KARIM SADJADPOUR: Well, to
begin, he was a
close confidant of the father of
the Islamic

18:26.472 --> 18:29.108 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Revolution, Ayatollah Khomeini.

18:29.141 --> 18:34.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think what was unique
about Rafsanjani
was that he was always the
cleric in Iran

18:34.213 --> 18:38.651 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who was interested in putting
the country's
interests, namely, its economic
interests,

18:38.684 --> 18:41.721 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
before revolutionary ideology.

18:41.754 --> 18:47.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But he ultimately lost that
battle against
the current supreme leader,
Ayatollah Ali

18:47.326 --> 18:51.364 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Khamenei, who always believed
that the revolutionary
ideology should come first.

18:51.397 --> 18:55.868 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, as you
wrote, you have
written in the last couple of
days, he helped

18:55.901 --> 19:01.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to put Khamenei, the current
ayatollah, in
power, but almost immediately
started trying

19:01.340 --> 19:03.376 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to get him out of power.

19:03.409 --> 19:04.377 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's a fascinating story.

19:04.410 --> 19:06.145 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
KARIM SADJADPOUR: It really is.

19:06.178 --> 19:09.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I call it Shiite Shakespeare,
like a Shakespearian
epic, because he was the
kingmaker.

19:09.849 --> 19:16.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He made Khamenei supreme leader
in 1989, thinking
that he could -- he would be
weak and pliant

19:16.956 --> 19:19.091 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and Rafsanjani could control
him.

19:19.125 --> 19:23.396 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think he spent the last
three decades
of his life trying to wrestle
power back from

19:23.429 --> 19:24.730 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Khomeini, unsuccessfully.

19:24.764 --> 19:29.435 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: They were two
very different
men, weren't they?

19:29.468 --> 19:32.271 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Why was one successful and the
other one wasn't
ultimately?

19:32.304 --> 19:36.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KARIM SADJADPOUR: Well, I think,
ultimately,
what was -- what made Khamenei
successful

19:36.409 --> 19:41.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is, I think he understood an
important Machiavellian
rule, which is, in authoritarian
regimes,

19:41.714 --> 19:44.550 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it's much more important to be
feared than
to be loved.

19:44.583 --> 19:50.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, Khamenei very carefully over
the last
couple decades had cultivated
the military,

19:50.289 --> 19:53.759 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Revolutionary Guard, and so
that was deeply
helpful to him.

19:53.793 --> 20:00.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the same time, whereas
Khamenei had a reputation
for being financially clean,
Rafsanjani and

20:01.000 --> 20:06.605 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
his family had a terrible
reputation of being
economically corrupt, which
provoked a lot

20:06.639 --> 20:08.407 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
