them.

20:08.441 --> 20:13.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Resentment, and
yet you're
telling us his death means a
great deal for

20:13.979 --> 20:15.748 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Iran.

20:15.781 --> 20:19.285 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KARIM SADJADPOUR: Well, yes, he
was one of
the pillars, the last two
remaining pillars

20:19.318 --> 20:25.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the 1979 revolution who
played a very important
role as a mentor to the younger
generation

20:25.391 --> 20:29.261 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of technocrats, and, as you
mentioned, President
Hassan Rouhani.

20:29.295 --> 20:34.467 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And he was kind of a
counterweight against
more radical forces in Iran.

20:34.500 --> 20:38.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that obituary writers
are very confused
about Rafsanjani, because, on
one hand, he

20:38.971 --> 20:41.207 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
was someone who had blood on his
hands.

20:41.240 --> 20:45.344 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He ordered the killing of
dissidents and intellectuals
within Iran.

20:45.377 --> 20:48.447 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was implicated in terrorist
operations
overseas.

20:48.481 --> 20:53.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, at the same time, in the
context of the
Islamic Republic of Iran, he was
more moderate

20:53.853 --> 20:55.321 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
than his peers.

20:55.354 --> 20:58.190 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, that was my
next question:
How moderate was he truly?

20:58.224 --> 21:03.262 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KARIM SADJADPOUR: So, in a
Western liberal
context, he wasn't a
Jeffersonian democrat,

21:03.295 --> 21:08.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but in the context of Iran, as I
said, he
favored putting the country's
economic interests

21:08.534 --> 21:14.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
before revolutionary ideology,
which meant
things that -- that he was
supportive of detente

21:14.206 --> 21:15.808 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
with the United States.

21:15.841 --> 21:20.045 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was supportive of a cordial
relationship
with Saudi Arabia.

21:20.079 --> 21:27.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he differed on these issues
of revolutionary
ideology, in contrast to the
supreme leader.

21:27.453 --> 21:32.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I think we
mentioned he was
a mentor to the current
president, President

21:32.291 --> 21:33.492 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Rouhani.

21:33.526 --> 21:36.562 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, what does it mean now that
he's gone from
the scene?

21:36.595 --> 21:39.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What do you expect to see in the
months to
come?

21:39.899 --> 21:43.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KARIM SADJADPOUR: I think May
2017 will be
the first litmus test.

21:44.003 --> 21:45.871 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's Iran's presidential
elections.

21:45.905 --> 21:49.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think we have learned in the
United States
that predicting presidential
elections even...

21:49.275 --> 21:51.076 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: We have learned
that.

21:51.110 --> 21:53.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KARIM SADJADPOUR: We have
learned -- even
in a democratic system is
difficult, let alone

21:53.546 --> 21:56.949 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in an opaque, authoritarian
system like Iran.

21:56.982 --> 22:03.789 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You know, I made the comparison,
I make the
comparison with Bill Clinton.

22:03.822 --> 22:07.393 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Rafsanjani was an elder
statesman of Iranian
politics.

22:07.426 --> 22:09.728 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He served as president of the
country.

22:09.762 --> 22:12.565 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But his political -- he didn't
have a political
future.

22:12.598 --> 22:14.934 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He had a prominent past.

22:14.967 --> 22:20.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I ultimately don't think
that this
is a game-changer for Iran, in
that the powers

22:20.472 --> 22:25.644 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that be currently, the supreme
leader, the
Revolutionary Guards, are going
to remain

22:25.678 --> 22:27.313 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the main powers that be.

22:27.346 --> 22:30.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, you know, an influential
counterweight
against them has now been
removed.

22:30.316 --> 22:34.753 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Karim Sadjadpour,
thank you
very much.

22:34.787 --> 22:43.596 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KARIM SADJADPOUR: Thank you,
Judy.

22:43.629 --> 22:48.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

22:48.133 --> 22:53.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
what to expect
from President Obama's farewell
address; and

22:53.505 --> 22:58.477 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
using art to boost math skills.

22:58.510 --> 23:04.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But first: As president, Mr.
Obama made a
pledge to shine a light on mass
incarceration

23:04.183 --> 23:06.118 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and criminal justice issues.

23:06.151 --> 23:11.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Among other things, he has used
his executive
power to grant clemency to more
people than

23:11.323 --> 23:13.626 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
any other president in modern
history.

23:13.659 --> 23:19.198 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As part of our series The Obama
Years, the
"NewsHour"'s Hari Sreenivasan
begins our coverage.

23:19.231 --> 23:24.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NORMAN BROWN, Released Prisoner:
"Dear Norman,
I wanted to personally inform
you that I will

23:24.703 --> 23:26.972 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
be granting your application for
commutation."

23:27.006 --> 23:30.576 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Norman Brown
is reading
the letter from President Obama
that gave

23:30.609 --> 23:32.611 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
him his life back.

23:32.645 --> 23:37.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For 24.5 years, he was in
federal prison for
selling drugs in Washington,
D.C., specifically

23:37.950 --> 23:40.419 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
six counts of distributing
cocaine.

23:40.452 --> 23:43.322 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was his third strike, and
that meant life
without parole.

23:43.355 --> 23:47.326 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NORMAN BROWN: I never thought
that I would
get no more than maybe 15 years.

23:47.359 --> 23:51.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: While he was
in prison,
his parents, his grandmother,
his brother

23:51.730 --> 23:56.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
all died, his children grew up,
and the men
sentenced with him were
released.

23:56.635 --> 24:05.311 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NORMAN BROWN: I wanted to get
out to prove
to people that I had a monster
sentence, but

24:05.344 --> 24:07.112 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I wasn't a monster.

24:07.146 --> 24:11.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Brown took
classes, taught
others, earned certificates for
trade skills

24:11.517 --> 24:13.285 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and was a model prisoner.

24:13.319 --> 24:17.456 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA, President of the
United States:
It is my strong belief that, by
exercising

24:17.489 --> 24:25.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
these presidential powers, I
have the chance
to show people what a second
chance can look

24:25.097 --> 24:26.965 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
like.

24:26.999 --> 24:29.601 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The president
explained
his motivation this year at a
lunch with clemency

24:29.635 --> 24:31.437 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
recipients, including Brown.

24:31.470 --> 24:37.676 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In 2014, Mr. Obama began a
large-scale clemency
project, reducing the sentences
of mostly

24:37.710 --> 24:43.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
nonviolent drug offenders, after
his administration's
efforts to overhaul the criminal
justice system

24:43.649 --> 24:45.684 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
failed in Congress the previous
year.

24:45.718 --> 24:49.922 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NORMAN BROWN: And being an
example for you
all is a part of my duty.

24:49.955 --> 24:52.491 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Brown has been
out for a
year now.

24:52.524 --> 24:56.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He mentors kids in the juvenile
justice system
as a volunteer for the
Washington Department

24:56.829 --> 25:01.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Youth Rehabilitation Services
and helps
former prisoners like him
reenter society.

25:01.834 --> 25:03.802 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NORMAN BROWN: It's about growing
up.

25:03.836 --> 25:07.706 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Steve
Wasserman of the National
Association of Assistant U.S.
Attorneys defends

25:07.740 --> 25:12.711 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the strict sentencing guidelines
that put
people like Brown behind bars
for so long.

25:12.745 --> 25:14.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVEN WASSERMAN, National
Association of
Assistant U.S. Attorneys: When
you look at

25:14.279 --> 25:19.151 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
recidivism rates in this
country, they range
anywhere from 50 to 75 percent.

25:19.184 --> 25:23.922 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The statistics would indicate
that a large
number of them will reoffend.

25:23.956 --> 25:32.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they will reoffend in a
variety of different
ways, which will victimize
people, the public.

25:32.064 --> 25:34.199 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's where our core
concern is.

25:34.233 --> 25:39.138 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: President
Obama has received
more than 35,000 petitions for
clemency in

25:39.171 --> 25:41.206 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the past eight years.

25:41.240 --> 25:51.984 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's granted 1,324; 1,176 of
those are commutations
that simply shorten a sentence;
148 are presidential

25:52.017 --> 25:58.123 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
pardons, which forgive a
person's conviction
and reinstate civil liberties,
like voting.

25:58.157 --> 26:03.695 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
There are still 12,000
commutation petitions
awaiting a decision before the
end of Obama's

26:03.729 --> 26:04.997 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
term.

26:05.030 --> 26:07.099 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Darren Perkins (ph) has filed
for one.

26:07.132 --> 26:12.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In 1993, he was sentenced to
life without
parole on conspiracy charges for
distribution

26:12.771 --> 26:15.874 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of crack cocaine in Washington,
D.C.

26:15.908 --> 26:19.278 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mandatory guidelines in effect
at the time
made it difficult to sentence
him with anything

26:19.311 --> 26:22.347 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
less than life in prison without
parole.

26:22.381 --> 26:27.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Perkins' family still lives in
the same D.C.
neighborhood and has stood by
him for the

26:27.085 --> 26:31.323 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
almost 26 years that he's been
locked up.

26:31.356 --> 26:34.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
His youngest child, Brandi
Patterson, was
born after Perkins'
incarceration.

26:34.593 --> 26:37.029 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRANDI PATTERSON, Daughter of
Inmate: My dad's
been in jail for 26 years.

26:37.062 --> 26:39.198 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think that he's definitely
served his debt.

26:39.231 --> 26:41.500 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He's paid his debt to society.

26:41.533 --> 26:43.836 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And he wasn't able to see his
children grow.

26:43.869 --> 26:47.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I feel like the little bit
of time that
he does have left with us, that
he should

26:47.239 --> 26:49.274 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
be able to experience it
physically.

26:49.308 --> 26:54.079 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Perkins'
eldest son, Delonte
Simon, knows his father was far
from perfect,

26:54.112 --> 26:57.683 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but wonders what life would be
like if his
arrest never happened.

26:57.716 --> 27:02.888 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DELONTE SIMON, Son of Inmate: Me
and Brandi
talked about, if our father was
out, how would

27:02.921 --> 27:05.090 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we be or how would things be
with our family?

27:05.123 --> 27:06.091 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Would we be the same people?

27:06.124 --> 27:07.092 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Would our family be as strong as
it is now?

27:07.125 --> 27:08.427 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What, we don't know.

27:08.460 --> 27:12.264 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, at the end of the day,
everything happens
for a reason.

27:12.297 --> 27:15.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Even the judge
who sentenced
him to life sent a letter to the
president

27:15.934 --> 27:20.305 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
saying he would have imposed a
shorter sentence
if the law had allowed it.

27:20.339 --> 27:24.076 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Perkins told the "NewsHour" in
an e-mail from
prison that he will continue to
fight for

27:24.109 --> 27:28.547 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
his freedom, but is unsure what
a Trump administration
will mean for his future.

27:28.580 --> 27:34.286 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
DONALD TRUMP (R),
President-Elect: I am the
law and order candidate.

27:34.319 --> 27:36.121 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

27:36.154 --> 27:40.292 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN:
President-elect Trump has
been silent on his plans for
clemency, but

27:40.325 --> 27:45.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
his pick for attorney general,
Senator Jeff
Sessions, made it clear in a
2014 press release

27:45.864 --> 27:48.734 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that the current administration
has overstepped.

27:48.767 --> 27:52.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Sessions called the president's
sentencing
reform efforts -- quote -- "a
thumb in the

27:52.404 --> 27:57.342 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
eye of law enforcement officers,
prosecutors,
defense attorneys, judges, court
and prison

27:57.376 --> 27:59.177 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
personnel."

27:59.211 --> 28:03.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Wasserman says the reason why
President Obama
is granting massive amounts of
clemency are

28:03.282 --> 28:05.050 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the major problem.

28:05.083 --> 28:10.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVEN WASSERMAN: He's granting
essentially
mass commutations simply because
he disagrees

28:10.989 --> 28:16.862 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with the law as duly passed by
Congress.

28:16.895 --> 28:24.102 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we believe that that is an
historical
break from previous presidents'
exercise of

28:24.136 --> 28:25.904 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
that power.

28:25.938 --> 28:29.107 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: While Perkins
and his family
wait and hope to receive a
letter from the

28:29.141 --> 28:30.943 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
president...

28:30.976 --> 28:33.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NORMAN BROWN: "I am granting
your application
because you have demonstrated
the potential

28:33.612 --> 28:35.247 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to turn your life around."

28:35.280 --> 28:38.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: ... Norman
Brown knows the
responsibility that comes with
it.

28:38.750 --> 28:43.722 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Even the president in his letter
tells you
people are going to doubt you,
whether you

28:43.755 --> 28:47.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are reformed, whether you can
live a clean,
good life.

28:47.693 --> 28:49.227 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I mean, it's a challenge.

28:49.261 --> 28:50.429 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
NORMAN BROWN: Yes.

28:50.462 --> 28:54.232 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I wouldn't want to let him
down.

28:54.266 --> 29:01.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I wouldn't want to let --
because to let him
down means that the process of
clemency doesn't

29:01.740 --> 29:04.576 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
work.

29:04.610 --> 29:12.017 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I say that because of the
fact that, if
we are not given a second
chance, that means

29:12.050 --> 29:20.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a lot of us who have talents
that society
can use will just dry-rot in
jail.

29:20.258 --> 29:22.427 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And society needs what we have
to offer.

29:22.461 --> 29:26.064 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Yes, we made a mistake, but who
hasn't?

29:26.098 --> 29:28.967 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
"So, good luck.

29:29.001 --> 29:29.935 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Godspeed.

29:29.968 --> 29:32.638 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Sincerely yours, President
Obama."

29:32.671 --> 29:35.941 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: For the "PBS
NewsHour,"
Hari Sreenivasan, Waldorf,
Maryland.

29:35.974 --> 29:40.979 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And in addition
to the president's
record on executive clemency, we
wanted to

29:41.013 --> 29:45.617 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
take a broader look at his
overall record
on criminal justice reform.

29:45.651 --> 29:47.519 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
William Brangham has that look.

29:47.552 --> 29:52.524 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: President
Obama often points
out that the U.S. is 5 percent
of the world's

29:52.557 --> 29:56.161 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
population, but has over 20
percent of the
world's prisoners.

29:56.194 --> 30:00.032 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
His administration has tried
various initiatives
to change that reality.

30:00.065 --> 30:02.334 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But how successful has that
effort been?

30:02.367 --> 30:04.436 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I'm joined now by Wesley Lowery.

30:04.469 --> 30:09.274 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He's a reporter for The
Washington Post who
won a Pulitzer Prize for his
work on policing,

30:09.307 --> 30:11.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and he's the author of the book
"They Can't
Kill Us All."

30:11.810 --> 30:13.945 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I'm joined by Bill McCollum.

30:13.979 --> 30:18.016 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's a former congressman from
Florida and
former attorney general of the
state.

30:18.050 --> 30:19.518 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's now a lawyer in private
practice.

30:19.551 --> 30:21.586 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Welcome, gentlemen, to you both.

30:21.620 --> 30:23.622 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Wesley Lowery, I would like to
start with
you.

30:23.655 --> 30:28.060 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the things that is one of
the most
dramatic efforts that the Obama
administration

30:28.093 --> 30:34.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has made is the Department of
Justice intervening
in local police departments to
try to stamp

30:34.566 --> 30:36.501 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
out what they see as abuses
there.

30:36.535 --> 30:40.439 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This has happened in almost two
dozen police
departments around the country.

30:40.472 --> 30:43.942 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Broadly speaking, can you tell
us, what are
they trying to do, and how
successful has

30:43.975 --> 30:45.811 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that effort been?

30:45.844 --> 30:48.013 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WESLEY LOWERY, The Washington
Post: What we
see in these cases has been a
very aggressive

30:48.046 --> 30:49.915 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Civil Rights Division of the
Department of
Justice.

30:49.948 --> 30:53.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so what they would do in a
case like Ferguson
or Baltimore is send federal
investigators

30:53.952 --> 30:56.988 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to that town, to that city to
conduct investigations.

30:57.022 --> 30:59.624 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They would request reams of
data.

30:59.658 --> 31:01.526 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They would dig through internal
documents.

31:01.560 --> 31:05.664 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what they were essentially
doing is preparing
a prosecution document, these
reports that

31:05.697 --> 31:11.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you would see, in which the
Department of
Justice would lay out their case
for litigation.

31:11.103 --> 31:15.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They would argue that a police
department
is violating the civil rights of
its residents,

31:15.474 --> 31:19.177 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
whether it be through traffic
stops or through
use of force.

31:19.211 --> 31:23.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it would lay those things
out, essentially
with the threat to sue the city
and sue the

31:23.381 --> 31:25.117 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
department.

31:25.150 --> 31:28.253 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In order to prevent that
lawsuit, many of
these departments and these
cities would enter

31:28.286 --> 31:32.424 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what are called federal consent
decrees, and
so -- in which the city and
department agree

31:32.457 --> 31:36.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to a certain set of reforms and
agree to some
type of federal monitoring for a
period of

31:36.895 --> 31:41.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
time, something the Obama
administration has
used very aggressively in order
to try to

31:41.566 --> 31:44.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
force change to departments that
otherwise
might not have seen it, because
what we have

31:44.503 --> 31:48.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to remember is, the federal
government actually
has very little power over local
police departments,

31:48.807 --> 31:50.642 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
based on kind of our system of
government.

31:50.675 --> 31:53.178 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Policing is a small government,
local issue.

31:53.211 --> 31:56.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is one of the few ways that
the federal
government can actually make the
police in

31:56.281 --> 31:58.583 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
your town or your city behave
differently.

31:58.617 --> 32:01.153 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Bill McCollum,
I wonder
what your take on that is.

32:01.186 --> 32:06.424 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What is your sense of how the
Obama administration
has handled its efforts to
reform police in

32:06.458 --> 32:08.360 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the country?

32:08.393 --> 32:09.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BILL MCCOLLUM, Former Florida
Attorney General:
Well, I don't think, first of
all, that the

32:09.861 --> 32:12.030 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
need of reform of police is very
strong.

32:12.063 --> 32:13.865 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But they have gone into a few
communities.

32:13.899 --> 32:17.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't doubt that, out of the
thousands of
local police and sheriff's
departments, there

32:17.068 --> 32:19.371 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are some that need some kind of
attention.

32:19.404 --> 32:23.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the biggest problem I see
with the Obama
administration's approach is
that it's all

32:23.441 --> 32:25.343 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
civil rights-focused.

32:25.377 --> 32:30.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It doesn't recognize the fact
that the police
overall do a terrific job and
need more support.

32:30.582 --> 32:35.420 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Their morale is at an all-time
low today around
the country as a result of,
frankly, the president's

32:35.453 --> 32:39.791 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
lack of leadership or his
misdirection in
that leadership in the face of
some very serious

32:39.825 --> 32:42.294 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
incidents that I think did need
some attention.

32:42.327 --> 32:46.264 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Wesley Lowery,
in defending
his own record, the president
this weekend

32:46.298 --> 32:51.736 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
cited that we have seen
historically low levels
of crime during his presidency.

32:51.770 --> 32:53.972 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Can the president take credit
for that?

32:54.005 --> 32:56.842 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He is taking credit for it, but
is that a
legitimate thing to claim?

32:56.875 --> 33:01.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WESLEY LOWERY: You know, it is
certainly accurate
and true that we are seeing some
of the lowest

33:01.446 --> 33:04.049 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
levels of crime in the history
of the United
States of America.

33:04.082 --> 33:07.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Obama years are some of the
most peaceful
years in American history as it
relates to

33:07.853 --> 33:09.588 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
crime.

33:09.621 --> 33:12.157 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think New York City just had
the least violent
year in its modern recorded
history.

33:12.190 --> 33:17.796 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, that means very little to a
family living
in West Englewood, Chicago,
right, or in Englewood,

33:17.829 --> 33:21.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or in many of the neighborhoods
in Baltimore
and even here in D.C.

33:21.566 --> 33:25.403 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so we have -- what we have
certainly seen
is that the majority of the
country has become

33:25.437 --> 33:28.607 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
safer, and yet the places that
are dangerous
have become more dangerous.

33:28.640 --> 33:34.112 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Bill, one of
the other things
that President Obama has taken
great effort

33:34.145 --> 33:38.583 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at is trying to reduce what he
believes is
an epidemic of mass
incarceration.

33:38.617 --> 33:44.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He has signed laws that would
reduce mandatory
minimum sentences, change these
sentencing

33:44.322 --> 33:47.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
guidelines for crack cocaine vs.
powdered
cocaine.

33:47.659 --> 33:49.828 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What do you make of that effort
over the past
eight years?

33:49.861 --> 33:54.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BILL MCCOLLUM: Well, I think
he's right to
try to reduce the differences
between crack

33:54.699 --> 33:56.468 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and powder cocaine.

33:56.501 --> 34:00.839 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I don't have a problem with
granting clemency
on a case-by-case basis.

34:00.872 --> 34:03.074 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As attorney general of Florida,
that's something
that I did.

34:03.108 --> 34:06.177 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I was part of the clemency board
that met
every month.

34:06.211 --> 34:08.380 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But I do believe in minimum
mandatory sentences.

34:08.413 --> 34:12.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I do believe in deterrence that
is going to
come out of a determinate
sentencing.

34:12.951 --> 34:16.922 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
When I was on the Crime
Subcommittee in Congress
several years ago, we didn't
have that.

34:16.955 --> 34:21.092 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And instead, we had judges that
were widely
varied in the kind of sentencing
that they

34:21.126 --> 34:22.093 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
did.

34:22.127 --> 34:23.862 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And the messaging was terrible.

34:23.895 --> 34:26.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one of the reasons that we
do have this
lower crime rate today is
because we have

34:26.765 --> 34:32.404 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
locked up a lot of the bad guys
for long sentences,
and we have seen fewer of them
out on the

34:32.437 --> 34:34.239 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
street to commit those crimes.

34:34.272 --> 34:37.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I fear that we're going back
into a new cycle,
where everybody is saying, hey,
let's turn

34:37.542 --> 34:40.779 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
everybody out, and you haven't
rehabilitated
anybody in prison.

34:40.812 --> 34:44.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Wes Lowery,
obviously, we're
coming to the end of the Obama
administration.

34:44.582 --> 34:49.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the Trump administration has
signaled
at least in several of his
potential appointees

34:49.387 --> 34:51.523 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a different tide.

34:51.556 --> 34:54.459 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What do you think we're likely
to see in this
next administration?

34:54.492 --> 34:58.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WESLEY LOWERY: Well, I certainly
think we're
going to see a very different
tenor and tone

34:58.363 --> 35:00.165 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
from the administration.

35:00.198 --> 35:04.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have already begun to see
this in terms
of how many of these issues are
framed, right?

35:04.536 --> 35:08.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So while, for example, President
Obama or
Eric Holder was much more likely
to be talking

35:08.907 --> 35:14.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about something such as a police
shooting
or community distrust,
president-elect Trump

35:14.346 --> 35:17.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and his incoming attorney
general, Jeff Sessions,
have shown they are much more
likely to talk

35:17.716 --> 35:24.356 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about things such as supporting
police officers,
so-called war on police, and the
idea of,

35:24.389 --> 35:26.224 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you know, ridding things of
violent crime.

35:26.257 --> 35:29.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think very often, in our
partisan political
lens, we talk about either one
of those things

35:29.728 --> 35:34.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or the other one of those
things, when, in
reality, most police chiefs who
you talk to

35:34.566 --> 35:38.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
will note that both of those
things are things
that deteriorate the
relationships between

35:38.169 --> 35:39.237 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
police and communities.

35:39.270 --> 35:41.006 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

35:41.039 --> 35:42.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the Trump administration, it
is going to
be fascinating to see what the
posture of

35:42.640 --> 35:46.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the DOJ is towards these issues,
not just
policing, but criminal justice
broadly.

35:46.811 --> 35:50.915 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Jeff Sessions, you have an
attorney general
who is one of the people who on
the Hill has

35:50.949 --> 35:55.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
prevented the criminal justice
reform package
that has been proposed by a
bipartisan set

35:55.754 --> 35:58.023 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of senators and congressmen from
happening.

35:58.056 --> 36:01.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so it is going to be very
interesting
to see what, if any federal
leadership on

36:01.259 --> 36:05.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- in terms of either walking
back mandatory
minimums, which has been a major
focus of

36:05.864 --> 36:10.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Obama administration, issues
of clemency,
and then also issues of kind of
data collection.

36:10.168 --> 36:14.506 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It is going to be very
interesting to see
what, if at all is pursued by
the Trump administration

36:14.539 --> 36:15.673 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in those spaces.

36:15.707 --> 36:17.075 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Bill McCollum,
last to you.

36:17.108 --> 36:19.277 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What do you think the Trump
administration
will do in this regard?

36:19.310 --> 36:22.147 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BILL MCCOLLUM: Well, I like to
think they
are going to return to the
policies that the

36:22.180 --> 36:25.817 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Reagan and Bush administrations
of the '80s
and early '90s did.

36:25.850 --> 36:30.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that was to look at examples
like Boston's
policing, where they did
community policing,

36:30.088 --> 36:34.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and take examples and say, look
to local governments,
here's some money, federal
money.

36:34.192 --> 36:39.564 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Go do it, like the police block
grants that
were given out years ago, not
without some

36:39.597 --> 36:43.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
strings, but basically saying,
we want you
cops back out on the streets,
walking those

36:43.701 --> 36:47.405 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
beats, instead of being afraid
to do your
job, which they are today.

36:47.439 --> 36:51.076 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I would like to see and
believe that they're
going to also focus on the black
community

36:51.109 --> 36:52.777 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and the Hispanic community and
the minorities.

36:52.811 --> 36:56.347 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
That's where I think
president-elect Trump
has said he's going to do
things.

36:56.381 --> 37:01.252 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the best thing he can do is
to address
the black-on-black crime,
Hispanic-upon-Hispanic

37:01.286 --> 37:05.356 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
crime, the gangs that are there,
to try to
prevent the crime in the first
place and deter

37:05.390 --> 37:10.695 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
it, and then, of course,
arresting those who
really are the ones that are
making the trouble.

37:10.728 --> 37:21.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Bill McCollum,
Wesley Lowery, thank you both
very much.

37:21.206 --> 37:24.409 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WESLEY LOWERY: Thank you.

37:24.442 --> 37:29.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: President Obama
will deliver
his farewell address to the
nation this evening

37:29.781 --> 37:32.984 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
before a room full of supporters
in Chicago.

37:33.017 --> 37:38.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We discuss a little of the Obama
legacy and
look ahead to tonight's speech
with two historians,

37:38.690 --> 37:45.130 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"NewsHour" regular Michael
Beschloss, and
Annette Gordon-Reed of Harvard
University.

37:45.163 --> 37:47.465 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we welcome both of you back
to the "NewsHour."

37:47.499 --> 37:48.800 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Michael, let me start with you.

37:48.833 --> 37:51.469 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How often do presidents give
farewell addresses?

37:51.503 --> 37:54.973 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL BESCHLOSS, Presidential
Historian:
Well, George Washington began
the tradition,

37:55.006 --> 38:00.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but it's really been more a
thing of modern
times begun by Harry Truman, who
did one from

38:00.178 --> 38:04.015 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the Oval Office when he retired
in 1953.

38:04.048 --> 38:05.884 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But they don't always work.

38:05.917 --> 38:10.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The ones that really work are
when you have
the sense that the president is
sort of leveling

38:10.155 --> 38:16.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with you in a way that perhaps
he wasn't able
to during his four or eight
years in office.

38:16.261 --> 38:20.532 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, he's saying something that
you haven't
heard before with new candor.

38:20.565 --> 38:26.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the other thing is that when
he says something
that sounds as if it's a lesson
he's learned

38:26.137 --> 38:27.939 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that perhaps he didn't know
before.

38:27.972 --> 38:34.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The best example of this,
Eisenhower in 1961,
said, worry about the military
industrial

38:34.546 --> 38:36.381 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
complex.

38:36.414 --> 38:39.150 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was something that he had
been increasingly
worried about for a long time,
but this was

38:39.184 --> 38:41.019 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the first time he said it to the
public.

38:41.052 --> 38:45.456 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Annette
Gordon-Reed, of course,
it's speculation, but why do you
think President

38:45.490 --> 38:47.292 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Obama wants to do this?

38:47.325 --> 38:51.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANNETTE GORDON-REED, Harvard
University Law
School: Well, he's in an
interesting position.

38:51.696 --> 38:55.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The election didn't turn out the
way he probably
thought it was going to turn
out.

38:55.366 --> 38:59.971 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is a chance to cement his
legacy and
talk about the kinds of things
that he wanted

39:00.004 --> 39:01.639 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to do as president.

39:01.673 --> 39:06.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he is facing a situation
where people
might try to undo a good amount
of that.

39:06.311 --> 39:10.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think this is a good way
for him to
sort of lay a template, perhaps,
for historians

39:10.582 --> 39:13.218 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
later on, even though that's
almost an impossible
thing to do.

39:13.251 --> 39:18.556 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think it's a way for him
to talk about
his legacy, to sort of say to
the American

39:18.590 --> 39:22.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people what was important to
him, what he
thinks he accomplished as
president.

39:22.660 --> 39:26.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Michael,
there is some
reporting over the last few days
that the

39:26.431 --> 39:33.571 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
president may be rethinking how
he wants to
spend his post-presidency, given
the outcome

39:33.605 --> 39:35.139 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of the election.

39:35.173 --> 39:36.608 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Could this be part of that?

39:36.641 --> 39:38.676 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHAEL BESCHLOSS: Might very
well be.

39:38.710 --> 39:44.482 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He might spend a lot more time
replying and
criticizing things that Donald
Trump may be

39:44.515 --> 39:46.251 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
doing as president.

39:46.284 --> 39:50.588 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if that's true, he's got to
have some
kind of foreshadowing of that in
this speech

39:50.622 --> 39:52.323 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
tonight.

39:52.357 --> 39:55.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One thing everyone will be
wondering is, what
is his current thinking about
Trump?

39:55.660 --> 39:59.631 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Right after the election, he
seemed quite
moderate about it, hoping
perhaps to coax

39:59.664 --> 40:05.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Donald Trump to make more
moderate appointments
and more moderate policies than
he was expecting

40:05.169 --> 40:06.137 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to.

40:06.170 --> 40:08.039 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But that's all over now.

