be a success
tonight.

42:40.057 --> 42:43.761 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Annette
Gordon-Reed, how much
have presidents in the past have
been able

42:43.795 --> 42:48.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to sort of, I don't want to say
tinker with
their legacy, but, say, shape
their legacy

42:48.966 --> 42:50.401 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
post-presidency?

42:50.435 --> 42:53.638 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm thinking about Jimmy Carter,
but I -- but
there are other examples.

42:53.671 --> 42:58.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANNETTE GORDON-REED: Well, Jimmy
Carter has
done a wonderful job with his
legacy and sort

42:58.543 --> 43:02.580 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of changing what people think
about him in
his post-presidential years.

43:02.613 --> 43:07.084 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, for the most part, it's
very difficult
to set your legacy, because
every generation

43:07.118 --> 43:11.122 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of people asks different
questions and is
concerned about different
things.

43:11.155 --> 43:16.093 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, a president could say, oh,
this is what
I want people to focus on, but
other generations

43:16.127 --> 43:18.429 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
aren't really as concerned about
that.

43:18.463 --> 43:21.232 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, it's -- you know, it's a
gamble.

43:21.265 --> 43:24.902 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They do the best they can do,
but historians
are going to do what they're
going to do and

43:24.936 --> 43:28.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
write what they're going to
write based upon
the needs of their particular
generation.

43:28.973 --> 43:30.007 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What about that,
Michael?

43:30.041 --> 43:31.709 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHAEL BESCHLOSS: Annette is
absolutely right.

43:31.742 --> 43:35.746 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We cannot be spun, or at least
we'd like to
think that we cannot be.

43:35.780 --> 43:41.853 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the presidents who are
trying to -- too
overtly to try to say, here is
what you historians

43:41.886 --> 43:47.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and what you later Americans
should think
of my presidency, 30 or 40 years
later, they

43:47.492 --> 43:49.327 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
look silly.

43:49.360 --> 43:51.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And finally,
